Predictive models to differentiate between clickbait and non-clickbait headlines.

Problem Overview

“Clickbait” is online content whose main purpose is to attract attention and encourage visitors to click on a link to a particular web page. The dataset for this assignment consists of clickbait titles (drawn from known clickbait websites such as Buzzfeed) and non-clickbait article titles drawn from reputable sources. The goal of this assignment will be to train predictive models to differentiate between clickbait and non-clickbait headlines.

The goal of this assignment is to get hands-on practice with text featurization, advanced predictive modeling techniques such as Ridge, Lasso, and ensemble methods, and constructing ROC curves.

cb_data <- read_csv("clickbait_headlines.csv") %>%

#Steps 1 and 2: preprocess and tokenize
cleaning_tokenizer <- function(v) {
  v %>%
    removeNumbers %>% 
    removePunctuation %>% 
    removeWords(tm::stopwords(kind="en"))%>%
    stemDocument %>%
    word_tokenizer 
}

it_train <- itoken(cb_train$article_title, 
                   preprocessor = tolower,
                   tokenizer = cleaning_tokenizer, 
                   ids = cb_train$article_id, 
                   progressbar = FALSE)

it_valid <-itoken(cb_valid$article_title, 
                   preprocessor = tolower,
                   tokenizer = cleaning_tokenizer, 
                   ids = cb_valid$article_id, 
                   progressbar = FALSE)

# Step 3: create the vocabulary
vocab_train <- create_vocabulary(it_train)

#Include ngrams
vocab2 <- create_vocabulary(it_train,ngram = c(1L, 2L))

vocab_final <- prune_vocabulary(vocab2, term_count_min = 10, doc_proportion_max = 0.5)

2: Ridge and Lasso

Your goal going forward is to predict the “clickbait” target variable using a few different types of models. You’ll compare them to pick the best-performing model in terms of validation AUC.

  1. Using a grid of 100 lambda values ranging between 10^-7 and 10^7, find the optimal lambda for a Ridge-penalized logistic regression model. Plot the fitting curve and report the optimal lambda. (optionally, you can use cv.glmnet with k = 5 if you want)

Make predictions with your best lambda ridge model and store them as a variable called preds_ridge.

ANSWER TO QUESTION 2a HERE: 

# define a function to calculate accuracy
accuracy <- function(classifications, actuals){
  correct_classifications <- ifelse(classifications == actuals, 1, 0)
  acc <- sum(correct_classifications)/length(classifications)
  return(acc)
}

dtm_train<- as.matrix(dtm_train)
dtm_valid <- as.matrix(dtm_valid)

# Extract the 'clickbait' column
tr_y <- cb_train$clickbait
va_y <- cb_valid$clickbait


grid <- 10^seq(-7,7,length=100)

accs <- rep(0, length(grid))

for(i in c(1:length(grid))){
  lam = grid[i] #current value of lambda

  #train a ridge model with lambda = lam
  glmout <- glmnet(dtm_train, tr_y, family = "binomial", alpha = 0, lambda = lam)
  
  #make predictions as usual
  preds <- predict(glmout, newx = dtm_valid, type = "response")
  
  #classify and compute accuracy
  classifications <- ifelse(preds > .5, "YES", "NO")
  inner_acc <- accuracy(classifications, va_y)
  accs[i] <- inner_acc
}

# get best-performing lambda
best_validation_index <- which.max(accs)
best_lambda <- grid[best_validation_index]
best_lambda
## [1] 1e-07
# Train a ridge model with the best lambda
best_glmout <- glmnet(dtm_train, tr_y, family = "binomial", alpha = 0, lambda = best_lambda)

# Make predictions
preds_ridge <- predict(best_glmout, newx = dtm_valid, type = "response")
  1. Repeat part (a) for a Lasso-penalized logistic regression model. Store the predictions from your best model in a variable called preds_lasso.

ANSWER TO QUESTION 2b HERE: 

grid <- 10^seq(-7,7,length=100)

accs <- rep(0, length(grid))

for(i in c(1:length(grid))){
  lam = grid[i] #current value of lambda

  #train a ridge model with lambda = lam
  glmout <- glmnet(dtm_train, tr_y, family = "binomial", alpha = 1, lambda = lam)
  
  #make predictions as usual
  preds <- predict(glmout, newx = dtm_valid, type = "response")
  
  #classify and compute accuracy
  classifications <- ifelse(preds > .5, "YES", "NO")
  inner_acc <- accuracy(classifications, va_y)
  accs[i] <- inner_acc
}

# get best-performing lambda
best_validation_index_lasso <- which.max(accs)
best_lambda_lasso <- grid[best_validation_index]
best_lambda_lasso
## [1] 1e-07
# Train a ridge model with the best lambda
best_glmout_lasso <- glmnet(dtm_train, tr_y, family = "binomial", alpha = 1, lambda = best_lambda_lasso)

# Make predictions
preds_lasso <- predict(best_glmout_lasso, newx = dtm_valid, type = "response")
  1. Do the ridge and lasso models have the same best lambda? Will the two models have identical coefficients? Which has better validation AUC?

ANSWER TO QUESTION 2c HERE: The two model have the same best lambda. However, their coefficients will likely not be identical due to the different penalty terms. Ridge regression tends to shrink coefficients towards zero but rarely sets them exactly to zero, while lasso regression tends to set some coefficients exactly to zero. The ridge model has better validation AUC.

# Compute the AUC for the Ridge model
pred_ridge <- prediction(preds_ridge, va_y)
perf_ridge <- performance(pred_ridge, "auc")
auc_ridge <- perf_ridge@y.values[[1]]

# Compute the AUC for the Lasso model
pred_lasso <- prediction(preds_lasso, va_y)
perf_lasso <- performance(pred_lasso, "auc")
auc_lasso <- perf_lasso@y.values[[1]]

# Compare the AUCs
print(paste("Ridge AUC: ", auc_ridge,",and Lasso AUC: ", auc_lasso))

rf.mod <- ranger(x = dtm_train, y = tr_y,

cleaning_tokenizer_new <- function(v) {

ANSWER TO QUESTION 5b HERE: When the vocabulary size increase, the accuracy on validation will increase as well. However, when the vocabulary size is too big, the model will overfit and the validation accuracy will decrease.

it_valid_new <-itoken(cb_valid$article_title, 
                   preprocessor = tolower,
                   tokenizer = cleaning_tokenizer_new, 
                   ids = cb_valid$article_id, 
                   progressbar = FALSE)

# Initialize vector to store validation accuracies
auc_r <- c()
val_accs <- c()

# Range of vocabulary sizes
vocab_sizes <- seq(10, nrow(vocab2_new), by = 100)

for (vocab_size in vocab_sizes) {
  print(paste("Processing vocab_size:", vocab_size))
  # Prune vocabulary
  pruned_vocab <- vocab2_new[1:vocab_size, ]
  
  # Create a vectorizer with the pruned vocabulary
  vectorizer <- vocab_vectorizer(pruned_vocab)
  
  # Vectorize training and validation data
  dtm_train <- create_dtm(it_train_new, vectorizer)
  dtm_val <- create_dtm(it_valid_new, vectorizer)
  
  print(dim(dtm_train))
  print(dim(dtm_val))
  
  # Train Ridge model
  model <- glmnet(dtm_train, tr_y_num, alpha = 0, lambda = best_lambda)
  
  # Compute validation accuracy
  preds <- predict(model, newx = dtm_val)
  val_acc <- sum((preds >= 0.5) == va_y_num) / length(va_y_num)
  
  # Store validation accuracy
  val_accs <- c(val_accs, val_acc)
  
  # Create a prediction object
  pred_obj_r <- prediction(preds, va_y_num)

  # Compute the AUC
  perf_obj_r <- performance(pred_obj_r, measure = "auc")
  auc_r <- c(auc_r, perf_obj_r@y.values[[1]])
  print(paste("Current length of auc_r:", length(auc_r)))
}
